author: Staff Reports
title: High school roundup
text:
High school roundup By Staff Reports sports@onlineathens.com – updated Sunday, October 11, 2015 - 11:43pm 
JEFFERSON | Top-seeded Oconee County needed all five sets to capture the Region 8-AAA volleyball championship Saturday, defeating No. 2 seed Jefferson 24-17, 22-25, 23-25, 25-18, 15-10. Earlier in the day, the Warriors (28-12) bested the Dragons (34-7) in the region semifinals 25-17, 25-17. 
Oconee County, which didn’t lose a match this season against region opponents, was led by Erin Brown (15 kills), Rachel Blanton (13 kills), Maggie Carlson (13 kills), Ansley McClain (55 assists, five aces) and Emily Boswell (43 digs). 
Jefferson, which also defeated Morgan County 25-9, 25-3 on Saturday, was led by Abby Wood (38 digs, 22 kills, five aces), Bre Arbanas (17 kills, five aces), Grace Haney (34 assists, six aces), Lindsey Nilsen (19 kills), Madison Corbett (42 assists, eight digs) and Olivia Przybysz (46 digs). East Jackson finished fourth and qualified for the Class AAA state tournament a victory over Hart County (25-17, 25-16) and a loss to Morgan County (27-25, 21-25). The Eagles (16-11) set a school record of wins in a season, and Emi Melendez and Sydney Mathis both received all-area honors. 
In the first round of the Class AAA tournament, which begins Wednesday, Oconee County will host South Atlanta, Jefferson will host North Clayton and East Jackson will play at Jackson. 
ATHENS ACADEMY WINS 199TH TITLE 
At Bogart, Athens Academy blanked Hebron Christian twice to win the Area 6-A championship, the 199th region or area title in school history. The Spartans (34-2), who did not lose a match to an area opponent this fall, defeated Hebron Christian 25-7, 25-22 and 25-14, 25-21, 25-15 to claim the area crown and earn a No. 1 seed in the Class A state tournament. 
Athens Academy will host Whitefield Academy — the No. 4 seed from Area 5-A — on Wednesday . Hebron Christian, George Walton and Tallulah Falls are the other area teams that made the state tournament. 
At Bethlehem, Winder-Barrow had a long but productive day as the Bulldoggs won two of three matches to advance to the Class state tournament. 
Winder-Barrow (30-20) opened the day by eliminating Apalachee (25-17, 14-25, 25-17) and then the Bulldoggs defeated Clarke Central 22-25, 25-7, 24-21 before bowing to Lanier (22-25, 22-25). 
Winder-Barrow will play Wednesday at Chapel Hill (16-13-1), the Region 5-AAA champion. 
At East Jackson Park in Nicholson, the final day of the Region 8-A tournament was rained out and is expected to be made up today. 
Prince Avenue Christian (15-17) and George Walton Academy (11-9) — both of which have yet to be defeated in the tournament — will meet at noon, as will Athens Christian (15-10) and Providence Christian (5-13), both of which have one loss. If Athens Christian is victorious, the Eagles will face the loser between Prince Avenue and George Walton at 2 p.m. The championship round will begin at 4 p.m. and all games must be finished by 9 p.m. for power ranking purposes. 
KENNEDYS, MORALES LEAD EAST JACKSON 
At Foxhall Sporting Club in Douglasville, East Jackson’s Chase Kennedy won the boys championship race of the Alexander Invitational, finishing first among 187 runners in a time of 15 minutes, 32.21 seconds. Chandler Kennedy was eighth in 15:53.03, and Oconee County’s Michael Hans came in 14th in 16:06.57. East Jackson finished ninth among 27 teams. 
In the girls championship race, East Jackson’s Sue Ann Morales finished third among 161 entrants in 18:03.12. 
In the girls 1A-4A race, Caroline McArthur of Oconee County finished seventh among 145 runners in 21:16.60 and the Warriors came in fourth among 20 teams. In the girls 5A-6A race, Kacie Wilson of Winder-Barrow was fourth among 201 runners in 20:24.85, and teammate Micah Weathers finished 12th in 21:07.72.
